Current Medical Status
Purpose of Referral:
Member referred to CM related to a diagnosis of diverticulitis with perforation and abscess. Member enrolled in CM 2/7/24.
History of Condition:
Member presented to Moses Cone Memorial Hospital ED on 1/11/24 with complaints of nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, and left lower quadrant abdominal pain. A CT of the
abdomen and pelvis showed acute sigmoid diverticulosis with fistulous tracts extending to the left pelvic sidewall and left anterior abdominal wall. Member was admitted for
further work up. She was placed on a nothing by mouth diet. Her condition continue to decline with a fever of 101f on 1/14/24. Intravenous antibiotics were started and
attempts were made to progress to a clear liquid diet. Her fever rose to 102f on 1/17/24. Further work up revealed diverticulitis with intramural abscess. She underwent
exploratory laparotomy on 1/17/24 resulting in a colon resection with ostomy. Her condition stabilized and she was discharged home on 1/22/24.
Member reports that she is recovering well post op. She reports that she and her sister are independent with routine ostomy care to include device changes twice weekly. She
is established with Moses Cone Ostomy Clinic. The Ostomy Clinic has facilitated ordering of supplies for her. Member will outreach the clinic for any delivery issues or
concerns. Member will return to Dr. Armando Ramirez on 2/12/24 for post-surgical follow up. Member does not have a PCP and declines CM assist with establishing with a
PCP at this time as she plans to move in the coming weeks. She will request assist from CM if needed after she relocates and gets settled in to her new home. CM provided
education on the importance of having a PCP and obtaining routine wellness with verbalized understanding. Member denies any comorbid disease processes and reports that
she is not on any prescribed medications.
Member returned for post op follow up as scheduled on 2/12/24. She reports that Dr. Ramirez is pleased with her post op healing. No complications to report. Member and
sister are adherent and independent with ostomy care as well as daily abdominal wound care. BMs within normal limits. Member will return for her next post op follow up in
April. Plan is for a post resection colonoscopy that will be discussed further and scheduled after her next follow up.
Member Social History:
Member is a 60 year old female with active benefits. She is currently out of work on leave post op with a release to return to work on 3/4/24. Member with supportive
sister/family that is staying with her at this time. No issue with finances to cover medication and other current medical services. No transportation issues reported that would
impact ability for her to attend medical appointments. Her sister provides all transportation. No cultural/spiritual barriers to care reported. PHQ2 is 0. No hearing or visual
impairments. Member denies alcohol, tobacco, or illicit drug use. ADs are not documented.
Current Medical Status:
Member reports no post op complications and has healed well. Stoma pink. Afebrile. Member and sister are adherent with ostomy care. BMs within normal limits. She receives
her ostomy supplies from Holister at no cost to her. Member states that she was to start STD after her LOA to get her through to return to work 3/4/24, but her employer
informed her that she did not have STD benefits. Member states she signed up for STD with open enrollment but no premiums were taken from her paychecks and therefore
she is not eligible for STD. Employer informed her they are unable to remedy the error and her position was terminated. She has applied for unemployment and Medicaid. She
will be going to stay with her sister in Salisbury, NC and has applied with social services in that location. Member aware CM will need to close case. CM reinforced education
related to signs of post-surgical infection to include fever greater than 100.4f, foul smelling or pus like drainage from wound that is increasing, new pain and redness of wound,
to report to her surgeon promptly if noted with verbalized understanding. Member will adhere to treatment plan to include wound care, ostomy care, scheduled follow up
appointments. Member is not on any prescription medications.
Prognosis/Course of illness:
Treatment plan is appropriate for diagnosis.

Purpose of Referral:
Member referred to TOC CM related to a surgical inpatient admission 1/22/24-1/24/24 for a diagnosis of central cord syndrome to undergo a neck spine fusion. Member

History of Condition:
Member with a history of chronic radiculopathy with recent uncontrolled pain exacerbations. Member was a scheduled surgical admission to High Point Regional 1/22/24-

comorbid conditions are well managed. A1c is 7, and blood pressure 127/78. He has remained on Tamoxifen maintenance therapy long term for prostate cancer and in
remission.
Member returned for post operative follow up with Dr. Cohen as scheduled on 2/20/24. He is healing well and without complication. He was instructed that he no longer needs
to wear his neck brace continuously but to wear if going on outings, car rides, activities for protection. He was referred for outpatient PT and began PT 2/29/24 with treatments
2-3 days per week for 6 weeks. He will return to Dr. Cohen for follow up on 3/19/24.
As of 3/14/24 follow up with member, he has attended OP therapy twice weekly as planned but with new complaints of numbness is his lower back and legs. He thought if he
gave it a few days that it may resolve since his last PT session, but did not resolve. He was unsure if he should attempt PT 3/15/24 as scheduled. Ibuprofen had not helped
this symptom. CM advised member notify Dr. Cohen promptly for direction and to hold PT in the interim. Member contacted Dr. Cohen 3/14/24 and was advised to hold PT
until his follow up on 3/19/24. Member was adherent with 3/19/24 follow up. An x-ray did not reveal any complications and post op surgery looked good on x-ray. It was felt that
it is related to normal post op nerve healing more so than a pinched nerve. He was advised to discontinue PT for now and was prescribed Gabapentin two to three times per
day. Member returned for post op follow up as scheduled 4/17/24. X-ray with some possible inflammation around L5. Plan is to increase Gabapentin to 800mg three times
daily and return for an injection to L5 on 5/14/24 if not resolved in the interim. Member unsure of what type of injection.

reported. PHQ2 is 0. No hearing or visual impairments. No alcohol, tobacco, or illicit drug use. Member is independent with all ADLs. ADs are not documented.

Member returned for post op follow up as scheduled on 5/14/24. He continues to experience tingling sensations in his lower back and legs. A steroid injection was
administered into his lower spine. Member understands that it can take 1 to 2 weeks for the injection to provide full relief. He states he had started feeling a little pain on top of
the numbness a couple of days prior to the injection and that pain has already resolved since the injection. He will return for follow up again on 6/5/24. Gabapentin continues at
Gabapentin 800mg three times daily. He is ambulating without difficulty and the symptoms are not affecting his independence with daily living. Reinforced reporting any
increased symptoms or pain to Dr. Cohen promptly if noted with verbalized understanding.
5/31/24: Unable to reach member for follow up. No inpatient admissions identified. Benefits now noted as termed. No mention of upcoming term by member with outreach

member on physiological signs of stress and depression and talked with member about the benefits of taking time off work when needed. Member reports that she used a
couple days of FMLA and that helped with decreasing her depression, she will check to see how many days of FMLA she has left. Member reports that she feels like her
therapist is not effective, and reports that conversations with CM tend to be more helpful than attending therapy. CM educated member on the different types of therapy
modalities and reassured member that it is okay to find a new therapist if the one she has is not providing education on skills to use outside the therapy setting to manage her
symptoms. CM offered to resend list of therapy providers that specialize in the treatment of alcohol abuse and depression to member, member instead requested for CM to
resend list of grief support groups via text.
